    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If your tomato plants are showing yellowing leaves without the typical spots, it might indeed be a nitrogen deficiency. Nitrogen is crucial for plant growth, and a lack of it can cause leaves to turn yellow, especially at the bottom of the plant where the roots are closest to the soil. To confirm if it's a nitrogen deficiency, you can check the color of the leaves. If the leaves are turning yellow while the veins remain green, it's a strong indicator of nitrogen deficiency. \n\nTo fix the soil, you can add a nitrogen-rich fertilizer to your tomato plants. Look for a balanced fertilizer with a higher nitrogen content, such as a 10-10-10 or 20-20-20 formula. Apply it according to the package instructions, and be careful not to over-fertilize, as this can harm your plants. Remember, too much nitrogen can lead to lush foliage but poor fruit production. It's also a good idea to test your soil's pH level, as tomatoes prefer slightly acidic soil (pH 6.0-6.8). Adjusting the pH can help your plants absorb nutrients more effectively. \n\nRemember, gardening is a bit like a game of strategy with your plants. You have to keep an eye",
